65
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:36,040
The results are, to put it mildly, disappointing.

66
00:05:36,040 --> 00:05:42,600
Only 5% of CHROs say that they have fully integrated AI into their HR operating model.

67
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:44,920
So readiness is pretty low.

68
00:05:44,920 --> 00:05:53,800
And even more telling, only 18% of CHROs say that they have gotten significant value from AI.

69
00:05:53,800 --> 00:06:00,280
And one in three actually say they have received no value from AI.

70
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,800
So what gives?

71
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:04,040
What's happening here?

72
00:06:04,040 --> 00:06:15,240
Well, there are three patterns that consistently explain why AI pilots stall and why value becomes so hard to achieve.

73
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:19,320
First, features outweigh outcomes.

74
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:21,960
I hear the story distressingly often.

75
00:06:21,960 --> 00:06:27,320
The CHRO will tell me, oh, we are under immense pressure in HR to use AI.

76
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:33,240
So we just turn to all of our vendors and ask them, hey, ABC, what AI features do you have?

77
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:38,200
And they gave us a list and we started checking them off one by one.

78
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:49,240
This is one of the biggest reasons why we are not getting value because we start with what the vendors have to offer rather than what we as HR want to achieve.

79
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:54,200
Second, AI deployments happen without AI readiness.

80
00:06:54,200 --> 00:07:03,160
Weak data foundations, limited workflow redesign, and underestimating adoption efforts make it hard to scale.

81
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:08,840
And finally, CHROs often struggle to prove and communicate tangible ROI.

82
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:16,640
Costs are often underestimated and benefits overestimated, or many benefits come across as soft and one-off.

83
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:22,560
In consistent value messaging damages confidence.

84
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:31,840
If HR can't show tangible impact, CHROs risk stalled pilots and accumulating technical debt.

85
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:36,720
Tools that just suck money and effort without results.

86
00:07:36,720 --> 00:07:43,200
So it's time for the CHRO to own the value story for AI.

87
00:07:43,200 --> 00:07:49,600
And that means using a three-step approach.

88
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:53,360
The first step is to set the North Star.

89
00:07:53,360 --> 00:08:06,320
Focus focus on those top two or three CEO and board level outcomes that matter most growth, margin, productivity, and define the outcome metrics that AI must move.

90
00:08:06,320 --> 00:08:16,080
That anchor in outcomes will help you being unduly swayed by will help you avoid being unduly swayed by features.

91
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:19,120
Step two is to decide where to play.

92
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:26,320
Prioritize the three to five HR processes where AI can have the biggest impact on those outcome metrics.

93
00:08:26,320 --> 00:08:34,960
Then build a balanced portfolio of use cases with both near-term safer bets and longer term high risk high reward bets.

94
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:40,720
That positions you to create measurable value while also building future advantage.

95
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:44,080
Step three is to design for value.

96
00:08:44,080 --> 00:08:50,000
Ready your data, processes, op model, and people to capture the value.

97
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,600
And then don't stop there.

98
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:59,400
Communicate it by estimating defensible benefits and consistently showing results over time.

99
00:08:58,960 --> 00:09:03,720
This is the golden path to AI value.

100
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:12,920
Set the North Star, decide where to play, and design for value.

