242
00:24:29,400 --> 00:24:36,520
So what you can do is use this as a starting point to build out your own use case assessment.

243
00:24:36,520 --> 00:24:44,920
So there are frameworks and tools available on Gartner.com that can help you bring your stakeholders together and build out uh this framework.

244
00:24:45,280 --> 00:24:54,240
Now, as you build these out, uh, one of the stories I hear from CHROs is that uh they are either under pressure.

245
00:24:54,240 --> 00:24:55,840
So I I see two camps here.

246
00:24:55,840 --> 00:25:04,400
They're either under pressure to show immediate short-term wins, or they have a stakeholder who said, Oh, I saw that ad from that vendor uh at the airport.

247
00:25:04,400 --> 00:25:05,360
Why don't we try that?

248
00:25:05,360 --> 00:25:05,600
Right?

249
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:08,400
So there's the shiny new object syndrome as well.

250
00:25:08,400 --> 00:25:15,120
So, what you need to understand is that there are three types of AI investments.

251
00:25:15,120 --> 00:25:20,240
The first one is AI investments or use cases within boundaries.

252
00:25:20,240 --> 00:25:29,760
So these are use cases where there's proven customers' uh success stories outside, you know the value, you know how much time it will take to get to value.

253
00:25:29,760 --> 00:25:37,360
And a great example is talent acquisition, especially the earlier parts of the recruiting process as we discussed.

254
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:39,600
The second one is pushing boundaries.

255
00:25:39,600 --> 00:25:44,880
This is where the value exists, but the extent is unclear.

256
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:47,920
So again, uh a great example is AI coaching.

257
00:25:47,920 --> 00:25:50,480
I know Lydia has just shared a great example.

258
00:25:50,480 --> 00:26:23,680
Another one is where um where it's a it was a frontline worker company, they had rolled out an AI coach to managers mainly for employee experience and manager effectiveness or soft squishy benefits, but the managers realized after six months of using the coach that they could get feedback on improving of all things, inventory management processes, and they ended up saving $10,000 per manager.

259
00:26:23,680 --> 00:26:31,320
So this was a this was a hidden store of value that they would have never reached had they said, Oh, this is a soft, squishy benefit.

260
00:26:31,320 --> 00:26:32,920
Let's not invest in this, right?

261
00:26:32,920 --> 00:26:34,440
So that's an example.

262
00:26:34,440 --> 00:26:39,400
Another one here is break the third type of investment is breaking boundaries.

263
00:26:39,400 --> 00:26:43,800
Here, 80% of projects will fail.

264
00:26:43,800 --> 00:26:53,880
You don't even know if the value actually exists, but you still pursue it for competitive differentiation, future readiness, and so on.

265
00:26:53,880 --> 00:26:57,880
And a classic example here is skills management.

266
00:26:57,880 --> 00:27:20,200
Now, almost all of the CHROs I speak with want to do something related to skills management, but very few, less than 10% actually get demonstable value from it because of several factors like job architecture, change management, um fragmented tech landscape and so on.

267
00:27:20,200 --> 00:27:24,440
But the ones who do succeed, they succeed spectacularly.

268
00:27:24,440 --> 00:27:38,440
So again, I was speaking with a consulting company the other day, and they were using skills to uh to infer consultants, uh they were using AI to infer consultant skills and map them to their next project.

269
00:27:38,440 --> 00:27:46,200
So this was significant improvement in efficiency, and it was also improvement in experience because it was much fairer.

270
00:27:46,200 --> 00:27:48,840
So, but that's a that's an exception, right?

271
00:27:48,840 --> 00:27:51,480
Very few people get that kind of benefits.

272
00:27:51,480 --> 00:28:05,160
So, what you need to do is avoid being fully fully focused on within boundaries, because if you do that, you lose a lot of the hidden value, the future readiness benefits.

273
00:28:05,160 --> 00:28:15,000
And you also don't want to go after the latest shiny new object, because if you do that, you don't have a solid proven base for ROI.

274
00:28:16,080 --> 00:28:19,280
What you need is a portfolio.

275
00:28:19,280 --> 00:28:23,920
And you need to decide what that portfolio is like for you.

276
00:28:23,920 --> 00:28:27,040
So these are some of the most common portfolios that we see.

277
00:28:27,040 --> 00:28:34,640
The first one is the conservative one that I was talking about, where you're fully focused on almost fully focused on within boundaries.

278
00:28:34,640 --> 00:28:41,840
Then you have FOMO, where you are betting heavily on the breaking boundaries use cases.

279
00:28:41,840 --> 00:28:51,280
And then there is optimized returns, which is much more balanced with about 70% within, 30% pushing and 10% breaking.

280
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:52,960
And the final one is interesting.

281
00:28:52,960 --> 00:29:11,360
And I usually see this in some leading financial services and high-tech companies where they take conscious decisions about investing in pushing boundaries and breaking boundaries use cases because that's directly tied to their strategic outcomes.

282
00:29:11,360 --> 00:29:14,480
So that's the disruptor persona.

283
00:29:14,480 --> 00:29:30,880
So you need to decide as a CHRO what's the portfolio that we want to achieve based on our strategy and our stakeholders' appetite and risk appetite and ambition.

284
00:29:40,240 --> 00:29:41,520
Lydia?

285
00:29:41,600 --> 00:29:42,480
Awesome.

286
00:29:42,480 --> 00:29:46,800
So let's move on to the third piece of it then, design for value.

287
00:29:46,800 --> 00:29:52,720
I would say this is probably the part of the webinar where everyone is waiting for, kind of going like, okay, but what am I supposed to do tomorrow?

288
00:29:52,720 --> 00:29:53,840
What do I have to think about?

289
00:29:53,840 --> 00:29:55,040
What do I need to calculate?

290
00:29:55,040 --> 00:29:57,520
Give me something on paper that I can actually use.

291
00:29:57,520 --> 00:30:01,800
And so we're hoping to spend the last little bit of our conversation specifically on this.

292
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:12,520
Now, before we get started, I would love to just kind of get a sense from the audience in terms of how would you rate your team's AI readiness when it comes to HR?

293
00:30:12,520 --> 00:30:14,680
The poll should be up on as usual.

294
