Okay, we're somewhere ready, somewhat there.

304
00:30:44,760 --> 00:30:47,640
I'm glad we're not seeing a I'm not sure answer yet.

305
00:30:47,640 --> 00:30:54,280
Although I will say there is no right or wrong answer to this one.

306
00:30:54,280 --> 00:30:59,800
All right, let's take a look here.

307
00:30:59,800 --> 00:31:03,640
Um I think we've got enough of a sample size.

308
00:31:03,640 --> 00:31:05,240
Uh, Robert, yeah, there we go.

309
00:31:05,240 --> 00:31:08,120
So most of us are somewhat ready, somewhat not ready.

310
00:31:08,120 --> 00:31:09,080
I get it, I get it.

311
00:31:09,080 --> 00:31:13,800
Sometimes you're just like, I don't know what I don't know, and I'm not ready to tell you that I actually know what's going on.

312
00:31:13,800 --> 00:31:39,880
And that is totally normal, and quite frankly, I I much rather have conversations in the I don't know what I don't know category than the I know exactly everything that is going on category because as you will see in later parts of this conversation as we're talking through a lot of the pitfalls, AI functions a little bit differently, and knowledge is one of those critical aspects that plays a very interesting role in how you configure and how you deliver value with AI.

313
00:31:39,880 --> 00:31:43,960
So, with that in mind, let's talk a little bit about AI readiness, right?

314
00:31:43,960 --> 00:31:47,280
So, what on earth does AI readiness even mean?

315
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:49,840
Again, it's a very big meaty topic.

316
00:31:49,840 --> 00:31:52,640
We've probably we can probably spend days talking about this.

317
00:31:52,640 --> 00:32:00,800
And I'm sure if you were to ever put this out in front of a leadership audience or your enterprise audience, you might get a few like stairs in the room as well.

318
00:32:00,800 --> 00:32:07,440
So, very, very simply, when you think about AI readiness, think about it in four different dimensions.

319
00:32:07,440 --> 00:32:14,080
And typically, when you're able to cover these four different dimensions, you've got the bulk of AI readiness assess and downpact.

320
00:32:14,080 --> 00:32:16,000
Number one, people readiness.

321
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:20,080
I know a lot of times when we talk about people readiness, we're like, okay, well, are they trained for AI?

322
00:32:20,080 --> 00:32:20,880
Can they prompt?

323
00:32:20,880 --> 00:32:22,160
Can they engineer?

324
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:28,240
Yes, and the and is in the question of are they motivated?

325
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:31,760
Do they have psychological safety to exercise the experiments?

326
00:32:31,760 --> 00:32:38,400
Are the systems designed so that's easier for them to use AI than it is to use the paper and pencil method?

327
00:32:38,400 --> 00:32:40,320
Because AI is a brilliant solution.

328
00:32:40,320 --> 00:32:54,240
But let's all be honest with ourselves here for a moment that if the AI solution requires three clicks and the good old Excel solution only requires one click, chances are most of us are still going to use that one click Excel solution, even if the AI solution is that much smarter.

329
00:32:54,240 --> 00:32:58,480
So, in that people readiness, don't forget the motivation of your stakeholders.

330
00:32:58,480 --> 00:33:03,280
Don't forget what makes them tick and what makes them adopt a solution a lot easier.

331
00:33:03,280 --> 00:33:06,800
The second thing you want to look at is process and governance readiness.

332
00:33:06,800 --> 00:33:13,360
So it's really asking the question: what changes in the work and how do we manage and control those changes?

333
00:33:13,360 --> 00:33:22,080
One of the things I always advise our clients on this one is that we have thrived as HR over the last two to three decades in participating in the process.

334
00:33:22,080 --> 00:33:28,160
We've measured ourselves in how fast we work, how quickly we turned around, how many tickets we were able to answer.

335
00:33:28,160 --> 00:33:30,000
AI changes that a little bit.

336
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:45,320
And that's where process and governance comes in because it's now HR's job to architect the system of how the work is done and not actively participate in the system because quite frankly, none of us are going to outrun the speed and pace of which AI can perform.

337
00:33:45,320 --> 00:33:47,480
And arguably that's not our strong suit.

338
00:33:47,480 --> 00:33:51,240
Our strong suit isn't designing that system of how work is done.

339
00:33:51,240 --> 00:33:54,360
The third piece of it is really around the technology readiness.

340
00:33:54,360 --> 00:33:58,680
So this is the can AI actually operate across your entire tech stack.

341
00:33:58,680 --> 00:34:09,320
And this is where we say, did you duct tape your existing solution with AI, or did you actually intentionally go and reinvent your workflows, your processes, and your tech stack with AI?

342
00:34:09,320 --> 00:34:17,560
Simple question, two entirely different meanings and two significantly different, I would argue, value delivery curves at the end of the day.

343
00:34:17,560 --> 00:34:19,640
And last but not least, is data ready.

344
00:34:19,640 --> 00:34:26,120
Now, when I say is data ready, I don't mean is your HRIS data ready to go and is 100% clean.

345
00:34:26,120 --> 00:34:39,320
Having started my career out in People Analytics, I will assure you that there is no such thing as 100% clean HR data because unless you say everybody stop, nobody move, even after a data clean exercise, something is gonna go wrong.

346
00:34:39,320 --> 00:34:43,880
Data readiness really looks at the aspect of are the characteristics documented?

347
00:34:43,880 --> 00:34:46,360
Do we have everything that we need captured?

348
00:34:46,360 --> 00:34:53,000
And do we have the architecture and the structure of data that is required to exercise AI?

349
00:34:53,000 --> 00:35:09,880
So, simplifying and boiling down a lot of the conversations that we're just having, here are some of the areas where we have seen things go south a little bit, and that we would caution against, if you will, as you're embarking on your AI transformation journey and looking to deliver value for the organization.

350
00:35:09,880 --> 00:35:14,760
Area number one where things derail from a value delivery perspective is actually people readiness.

351
00:35:15,040 --> 00:35:22,640
Because believe it or not, your ROI conversation in the organization happens much before the metrics are actually defined.

352
00:35:22,640 --> 00:35:26,800
And this goes back to the internal political capital conversation I brought up earlier.

353
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:34,640
Because a lot of times when we get excited about going in with AI, we start thinking about what could the success scenario look like, what could a win look like?

354
00:35:34,640 --> 00:35:36,000
And everyone feels great about it.

355
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:38,160
Everyone wants to own that win.

356
00:35:38,160 --> 00:35:42,880
But very few of us pause and ask, what does a failure look like?

357
00:35:42,880 --> 00:35:47,280
And if we were to have a failure, who is responsible for that failure?

358
00:35:47,280 --> 00:35:56,480
And that question is incredibly important because AI has exponentially grown the number of stakeholders required in an enterprise transformation program.

359
00:35:56,480 --> 00:36:03,200
Before it used to be IT rolled out the system, they own it, HR rolled out the system, they own it, et cetera, et cetera.

360
00:36:03,200 --> 00:36:08,080
Now, if you're rolling out an HR virtual assistant, IT could own the platform.

361
00:36:08,080 --> 00:36:09,600
You can own the process.

362
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:14,400
Someone else can own the actual SME subject matter expertise and the content.

363
00:36:14,400 --> 00:36:18,160
So when an employee doesn't get the right answer, who is it?

364
00:36:18,160 --> 00:36:33,280
If you haven't gone down the path of defining that level of ownership and going through the discomfort of having that conversation, that could be a missed opportunity and quite frankly a hidden trigger for a lot of the times when ROI cases start to fail.

365
00:36:33,280 --> 00:36:37,040
The second area we look at is process documentation and readiness.

366
00:36:37,040 --> 00:36:38,720
I mean, let's be honest with ourselves.

367
00:36:38,720 --> 00:36:45,280
There is always how we think the work is done in the organization and how the work is actually done in the organization.

368
00:36:45,280 --> 00:36:51,760
There is a reason why all of us have at least 10 different Excel spreadsheets manually tracking things going on somewhere.

369
00:36:51,760 --> 00:36:52,960
That's not an issue.

370
00:36:52,960 --> 00:36:59,520
Where the issue comes in is when you don't spend the time on the onset to discover those hidden processes.

371
00:36:59,800 --> 00:37:04,040
Because AI works on existing knowledge and existing processes.

372
00:37:04,040 --> 00:37:10,760
So unless you kind of discover this, what could very well end up happening is that you're going to go on an AI transformation.

373
00:37:10,760 --> 00:37:24,600
You're going to implement this great solution with very promising value, only to come to realize that this entire solution is predicated on five Excel files that are manually updated by two people in your organization on a weekly basis.

374
00:37:24,600 --> 00:37:30,760
And the entire system is hinged on those two people delivering the technology automation.

375
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:33,560
Not exactly an ideal outcome.

376
00:37:33,560 --> 00:37:36,840
Last but not least, we also look at technology readiness, right?

377
00:37:36,840 --> 00:37:46,600
This is where we encourage everyone, if you're working with a vendor solution or any technology solution, regardless if it's your IT team that's providing it or a vendor that's providing it.

378
00:37:46,600 --> 00:37:49,080
Always, always, always ask the question.

379
00:37:49,080 --> 00:37:51,880
How do I know it's not working?

380
00:37:51,880 --> 00:37:53,240
Because it gives you two things.

381
00:37:53,240 --> 00:38:01,160
Number one, it tells you if your vendor is in it for you and if they're in it to be your partner, and if your IT team are in it to be your partner.

382
00:38:01,160 --> 00:38:08,680
And number two, it allows you to think through those early trigger signs, those early warning signs about systems not working.

383
00:38:08,680 --> 00:38:19,800
So you can hit that pause button or you can hit that stop button much before the actual go live, and when you're starting to hemorrhage more costs and expenses related to the solution.

384
00:38:19,800 --> 00:38:23,160
All of this comes together to provide data.

385
00:38:23,480 --> 00:38:25,240
Remember what I mentioned earlier?

386
00:38:25,240 --> 00:38:27,960
Data isn't just HR system data.

387
00:38:27,960 --> 00:38:43,000
It is about how you have prepared your people, how you have documented your process even previous outcomes, and how you're working with your technology vendors and using all of that to enable the conversation in HR.

388
00:38:43,160 --> 00:38:46,640
Harsh, great.

389
00:38:44,200 --> 00:38:52,880
So yeah, so once you're ready to capture value, you need to measure it, like uh like Idia said.

390
00:38:52,880 --> 00:38:58,320
And the first thing to remember is that not all value looks the same.

391
00:38:58,320 --> 00:39:11,040
Depending on the outcomes that you prioritized in step one, you could be measuring productivity gains, cost savings or avoidance, improvements in experience and effectiveness and and so on.

392
00:39:11,040 --> 00:39:22,800
So here you you can see productiveness, uh productivity being highlighted, uh, and uh a set of metrics that you could use to demonstrate uh the productivity gains.

393
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:25,600
Now, two big pitfalls to avoid here.

394
00:39:25,600 --> 00:39:30,560
Number one, don't forget the baselines and attributions.

395
00:39:30,560 --> 00:39:36,240
So if you don't know where you're starting from, you won't be able to show how AI made an impact.

396
00:39:36,240 --> 00:39:48,480
And if you don't have, I know some clients who build out uh control groups and pilot groups to show that it's AI that's actually making the difference rather than something else happening in the organization.

397
00:39:48,480 --> 00:39:58,640
And second, if you do use uh I review a lot of HR AI business cases, and many of them are built fully on vendor supply benchmarks.

398
00:39:58,640 --> 00:40:13,120
Now that is good, but the challenge is in many cases, those benchmarks are not contextualized to your organization's size, geography, industry, and so on.

399
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:18,400
So that's it's it's it's very open to being challengeable, right?

400
00:40:18,400 --> 00:40:24,160
So this estimates won't be defensible if you just take benchmarks that are not contextualized.

